Amy Heckerling’s Place in Hollywood: Issues of Aging and Sisterhood in I Could Never Be Your Woman and Vamps -- tChapter 9 ‘Staying Young is Getting Old’: Youth and Immortality in Vamps -- tPart IV Reflections on the Heckerling Oeuvre -- tIntroduction to Part IV -- tChapter 10 “But seriously, I actually have a way normal life for a teenage girl”: The Teenage Female Empowerment Payoff in Amy Heckerling’s Clueless -- tChapter 11 Clueless Times at the Ferris Bueller Club: A Critical Analysis of the Directorial Works of Amy Heckerling and John Hughes -- tChapter 12 Way Hilarious: Amy Heckerling as a Female Comedy Director, Writer, and Producer -- tAppendix: Other Films and Television Shows Cited in this Collection -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA collection of interdisciplinary essays, collected for the first time, on the work of filmmaker and screenwriter Amy HeckerlingClueless and Fast Times at Ridgemont High are affectionately regarded as key foundations of the modern Hollywood teen movie. However, the director and screenwriter for these films, Amy Heckerling, is far from a household name, despite the major influence she has had on contemporary US cinema.The first book-length study of her films, ReFocus: The Films of Amy Heckerling brings together a collection of original essays from a wide range of critical perspectives, aiming to recuperate Heckerling’s place as a distinctive female voice in the contemporary Hollywood landscape. Divided into four sections, each examining a distinctive aspect of Heckerling’s work, the volume draws on research from applied linguistics and audience studies, as well as from aspects of gender and film studies. Questions of gender, genre and identity, as well as the role of women in Hollywood and the implications of Heckerling’s recent turn to television, are all considered in a volume that aims to refocus on the films and influence of this distinctive American director.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aMotion pictures, American. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Lindsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinch, Zachary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarro, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaklamanidou, Betty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeder, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarghitu, Stefania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Kimberly M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPress, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichards, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenman, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShary, Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aShary, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpeed, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107804440 cprintz978147440461740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474404624423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474404624/original  a978-3-11-078044-4  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKAL